  ('landmine-rotation', 'Creates a progressive rotational loading problem with a guided arc that is easier to coach than free twisting under load. Strength work gives the athlete more force and tissue reserve to express rotation later, but the load must stay controlled enough that the hips and trunk transfer force instead of the low back twisting under strain.', 'Creates a progressive rotational loading problem with a guided arc that is easier to coach than free twisting under load.', 'Belongs in Capacity because the main adaptation is progressive loaded strength, force production, tissue capacity, and structural reserve for rotational actions.', 'Use in the Capacity phase after any true Output work and before late conditioning. Keep load progressive and reps repeatable.', 'Loading rotation before the athlete can brace, hinge, lunge, or control the rib-pelvis relationship; do not chase heavy twisting volume.', 'Progress by load, range, stance challenge, tempo, or asymmetry. Regress by reducing load, lever length, band/cable tension, or rotational amplitude.'),
