  ('pivot-to-sprint-start', 'Finishes the library by connecting rotational body orientation to first-step projection and short acceleration. Rotational power improves when the athlete can sequence force from the ground into the hips, trunk, shoulders, and implement or direction change. Low reps and full rest preserve speed, accuracy, and tissue safety.', 'Finishes the library by connecting rotational body orientation to first-step projection and short acceleration.', 'Belongs in Output because the main adaptation is freshness-sensitive rotational power, speed, jumping, throwing, cutting, or acceleration quality.', 'Use early in the main session after warm-up and movement prep, before heavy strength, long sport blocks, or conditioning. Rest fully between attempts.', 'Using high-intent throws, jumps, cuts, or sprints as conditioning. Rotational power is lost when reps become slow, inaccurate, painful, or sloppy.', 'Progress one variable at a time: implement load, speed, approach, angle, distance, cue uncertainty, or rebound demand. Regress to static stance, lighter ball, lower speed, or stick finish first.')
